Url.Title: Welcome to Navigator 2 Help
Url.Abstract: TA Instruments Rheology Navigator 2 software allows you to carry out many functions and experiments, without the need for operator intervention. This means that you can automatically perform many routine experiments and repeat runs.

Url.Title: Using Navigator
Url.Abstract: Using Navigator There are essentially three ways to use Navigator with either existing scripts or new scripts.

Url.Title: Constructing Scripts Using the Record Mode
Url.Abstract: Constructing Scripts Using the Record Mode Script construction is very simple using the "Record" Mode. The Record Mode enables you to construct scripts in a logical fashion directly from within Rheology Advantage software. All actions in the Instrument and Data modules are recorded and put into script format. Additional lines for prompts, etc., can be added as the script is developed or during editing after recording is completed.

Url.Title: The Navigator Menu
Url.Abstract: The Navigator Menu An additional "Navigator" menu appears on the Main menu bar when you are using the "Record Mode" (under either Instrument or Data Module).

Url.Title: AutoInsert
Url.Abstract: AutoInsert When you develop a script, you should consider including certain rheometer functions. However, because there are so many things to consider, it would be very easy to forget some important functions. The warnings tab found on the Navigator options menu (in Instrument Control) ensures that these functions are recorded automatically in the script at the appropriate places.

Url.Title: Using Existing Scripts
Url.Abstract: Using Existing Scripts From the View menu in Navigator, select Script list. A list of the available scripts will be seen. Double click on the desired script to select it; the script will run automatically.

Url.Title: Statement Editor
Url.Abstract: Using the Statement Editor Although using the Record Mode is generally the easiest way to construct scripts, some functions that you may wish to include in a script cannot be accessed directly from within the Record Mode (e.g., Loop commands).

Url.Title: Variables
Url.Abstract: Variables Navigator supports two basic variable types, String and Numeric. Numeric variables can be Integer, Real or Time.

Url.Title: Using Conditional Statements
Url.Abstract: Using Conditional Statements Controlling Program Execution You can control the flow of your script with conditional statements and looping statements (constructs). Url.Title: Constructs Overview
Url.Abstract: Constructs Overview Constructs allow you to control the flow of the script by means of conditional branching, loops etc.

Url.Title: Case
Url.Abstract: Case All the statements immediately following a Case statement are executed (up to the next Case statement) if the integer value specified matches that evaluated in the Select statement.

Url.Title: Do
Url.Abstract: Do The statements following the Do are repeated until the WHILE condition is met. Example Do [statements] While (V1 >10)

Url.Title: Else
Url.Abstract: Else The If...Then...Else statement is used to evaluate whether a condition is True or False. Depending on the result, the statements between the If and the Endif or the Else and the Endif are executed.

Url.Title: Endif
Url.Abstract: Endif The If...Then...Else statement is used to evaluate whether a condition is True or False. Depending on the result, the statements between the If and the Endif or the Else and the Endif are executed.

Url.Title: EndLoop
Url.Abstract: EndLoop Terminates a loop. Example Loop (5) [statements] EndLoop

Url.Title: EndSelect
Url.Abstract: EndSelect Use the EndSelect function to define the end of a Select / EndSelect block. The parameter given in the Select statement is evaluated and then compared against each of the Case statements contained in the Select / EndSelect block.

Url.Title: Goto
Url.Abstract: Goto Specifies the name of a label to transfer control (jump) to. You can use the Goto function on it's own, or as part of a conditional statement.

Url.Title: If
Url.Abstract: If The If...Then...Else statement is used to evaluate whether a condition is True or False. Depending on the result, the statements between the If and the Endif or the Else and the Endif are executed.

Url.Title: Label
Url.Abstract: Label Create a label in the script. Use the Goto command to jump directly to this label. Example If V0 >2 then Goto EndIt [statements] :Endit

Url.Title: Loop
Url.Abstract: Loop Allows steps within a loop to be repeated a specified number of times. This command must always be terminated by an EndLoop command. (If the EndLoop command is omitted, the script will not verify.)

Url.Title: Select
Url.Abstract: Select Use the Select function to have Navigator execute one of several different groups of statements, depending on the integer value or expression given.

Url.Title: While
Url.Abstract: While All statements contained in the Do / While block are repeated until the condition specified here is met.

Url.Title: General Commands Overview
Url.Abstract: General Commands Overview

Url.Title: Beep
Url.Abstract: Beep Plays a sound to alert or inform the user. The beep type corresponds to the WAV file set in the control panel for the associated event.

Url.Title: Call
Url.Abstract: Call Calls the given script.

Url.Title: ClearMessage
Url.Abstract: ClearMessage Clears a message from the screen.

Url.Title: DisplayMessage
Url.Abstract: DisplayMessage Displays a message that requires no response. The message will remain on the screen until either a ClearMessage command or another DisplayMessage command is executed. The message will also be cleared if the script ends.

Url.Title: FlushPrint
Url.Abstract: FlushPrint Sends any print information stored with the Print command,to the printer.

Url.Title: LoadVariablesFromFile
Url.Abstract: LoadVariablesFromFile Loads and sets the values for all of the variables contained in the given variables file. Any variables already defined will be overwritten with the value contained in the variable file.

Url.Title: PauseDisplayFor
Url.Abstract: PauseDisplayFor Pauses the script for the given amount of time for the user to read the screen. Example

Url.Title: PlaySound
Url.Abstract: PlaySound Plays the given WAV file. Syntax PlaySound(<FileName>)

Url.Title: Print
Url.Abstract: Print Stores the given text and any variable in to the print buffer for sending to the printer with FLUSHPRINT.

Url.Title: PromptMessage
Url.Abstract: PromptMessage Displays a message that requires user acknowledgement before next step is executed (i.e., OK or Cancel).

Url.Title: PromptVariable
Url.Abstract: PromptVariable Allows the operator to enter a variable at runtime. PromptVariable(<Variable name>, <Message>, <Type>, <Low Range>, <High Range>)

Url.Title: PromptYesNo
Url.Abstract: PromptYesNo Prompts the user with a message requiring a yes or no answer. If the user selects "Yes," the return value is 1; if the user selects "No," the return value is 0.

Url.Title: SetProcList
Url.Abstract: SetProcList Allows a series of pre-stored procedures to be selected in order in which they are to be executed so that successive experiments can be carried out on the same sample without operator intervention.

Url.Title: SetString
Url.Abstract: SetString Stores the given text and variables into the string variable.

Url.Title: StoreVariablesToFile
Url.Abstract: StoreVariablesToFile Stores all currently defined variables (string and numeric) to the file specified. Navigator variable files can be loaded by means of the LoadVariablesFromFile command and provide a means of carrying values over from one run of the script to the next. Variable files can also be read in by any script, not just the one that created them.

Url.Title: ValueWithin
Url.Abstract: ValueWithin Test whether the value is within a percentage of the required value, returning 1 if it is, 0 if not.

Url.Title: Exp
Url.Abstract: Exp Returns the result of e to the given power. Example v0 = Exp (2) Sets Variable V0 to e^2

Url.Title: Exp10
Url.Abstract: Exp10 Returns the result of 10 to the given power. Example v0 = Exp10 (2) Sets Variable V0 to 10^2

Url.Title: Log
Url.Abstract: Log Returns the natural logarithm of the value. Example v0 = Log (2) Sets Variable V0 to the natural log of 2

Url.Title: Log10
Url.Abstract: Log10 Returns the base 10 logarithm of the value. Example v0 = Log (2) Sets Variable V0 to the base 10 log of 2

Url.Title: Maths
Url.Abstract: Maths Provides assignment, addition and multiplication for numeric variables V0 to V99 and string variables S0 to S99.

Url.Title: Pow
Url.Abstract: Pow Raises the first number to the second power. Example v0 = Pow (5, 2) Sets Variable V0 to 5^2 (i.e. 100)

Url.Title: Defining Math Operators
Url.Abstract: Defining Math Operators The mathematical operators provided by Navigator 2 (+ - * / 1n exp pow) enable almost any operations in discrete mathematics to be performed. Operations such as taking a root or performing a trigonometric (cos, sin, tan, etc.) or hyperbolic (sinh, cosh, etc.) function are very simple, and the relevant equations are in mathematics textbooks.
